  "prompt": "What is the best Perl web app framework?",
  "response": "The \"best\" Perl web app framework can vary depending on your specific needs, preferences, and the type of application you're building. However, a few popular and widely regarded frameworks in the Perl community include:\n\n1. **Mojolicious**: A modern, feature-rich web framework that is suitable for building both simple and complex applications. It offers a non-blocking I/O model, which makes it efficient for handling many simultaneous connections. Mojolicious also has built-in support for WebSockets, REST APIs, and more.\n\n2. **Dancer2**: A lightweight and easy-to-use framework that is particularly good for building small to medium-sized applications. It follows the \"write less, do more\" philosophy and is straightforward for developers familiar with other web frameworks like Ruby on Rails or Sinatra.\n\n3. **Catalyst**: A more feature-rich and mature framework that is well-suited for large applications. Catalyst is highly flexible and allows developers to create complex web applications. It has a steeper learning curve compared to Mojolicious and Dancer2 but offers powerful capabilities for those needing advanced features.\n\n4. **Twiggy**: While not a full web application framework, Twiggy is an asynchronous non-blocking HTTP server that is often used with other frameworks like Mojolicious for building high-performance web apps.\n\nUltimately, the best choice will depend on factors such as the scale of your project, your familiarity with Perl, the specific features you need, and your overall development philosophy. It's often a good idea to explore documentation and community support for each framework before making a decision.",
